description: {"blocks":[{"key":"bosvc","text":"Mitochondrial respirometry is key to understand how environmental factors model energetic cellular process. In the case of ectotherms, thermal tolerance has been hypothesized to be intimately linked with mitochondria capability to produce enough adenosine triphosphate (ATP) to respond to the energetic demands of animals in high temperatures. Recent studies made in Octopus maya proposed the hypothesis postulating that high temperatures could restrain female reproduction due to the limited capacity of the animals’ heart to sustain oxygen flow to the body, affecting in this manner energy production in the rest of the organs, including the ovarium. Until now, no reports have shown temperature effects and other environmental variables on cephalopod mitochondria activity because of the lack of a method to evaluate mitochondrial respiratory parameters on those groups of species. In this sense and for the first time, this study developed a method to obtain mitochondrial respirometry data of adult Octopus maya’s heart. This protocol illustrates a step-by-step procedure to get high yield and functional mitochondria of cephalopod heart and procedure for determining the corresponding respiratory parameters. The isolation procedures described here require two hours, demonstrating that confident and replicable results can be obtained with this method.","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":367,"length":12},{"style":"italic","offset":1004,"length":12}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Isolation of mitochondria from the systemic heart of adult octopus

steps.section: Isolation of mitochondria from the systemic heart of adult octopus

steps.section: Isolation of mitochondria from the systemic heart of adult octopus

steps.section: Isolation of mitochondria from the systemic heart of adult octopus

steps.section: Substrate/inhibitor titration (SUIT) analysis
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"3q2bl","text":"Observe a faster rate of oxygen consumption because of basal activity of the respiratory chain to counteract proton leakage from the inner mitochondrial membrane, which represents Respiratory State 2’ (S2’).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":202,"length":3}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"d38vt","text":"Record for ~5 min and then stop recording.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"32bte","text":"Record until the rate of oxygen consumption begins to drop.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9qlm2","text":"Add 1 µl of oligomycinA(5 mM oligomycin stock solution) to obtain a final concentration of 2.5 µM and induce Respiratory State 4’ (S4’o). With this procedure OXPHOS is inhibited by oligomycin and the rate of oxygen consumption begins to rapidly plateau (steady state).","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":12,"length":11},{"style":"bold","offset":131,"length":4}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"8chvg","text":"Record for ~ 2 min.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"ek40s","text":"Add 2.5 µM rotenone (Rot) plus 12.5 µM antimycin A (Ant) to obtain residual or non-mitochondrial respiration (ROX). Both compounds inhibit the electron transport system flux and induce a rapid decrease in oxygen consumption rate until it remains constant.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":21,"length":3},{"style":"bold","offset":52,"length":3},{"style":"bold","offset":110,"length":3}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
